**Declare an array ```nums``` and intialise position with  ```pos = -1```.**
**By using ```inorder()``` traversal push all elements in array ```nums```.
As mentioned in the problem, ```next()``` is valid, so no need to check for bounding conditions. Just increment the position value and return ```nums[pos]```.
Either ```{ pos++; return nums[pos]; }``` or ```{ return nums[++pos]; }```.
For ```hasNext()``` check whether next position is less than the size of the array nums using ```pos+1 < nums.size()```.**
```
class BSTIterator {
public:
    vector<int> nums;
    int pos = -1;

    void inorder(TreeNode* root) {
        if(root) {
            inorder(root -> left);
            nums.push_back(root -> val);
            inorder(root -> right);
        }
    }

    BSTIterator(TreeNode* root) {
        inorder(root);
    }

    int next() {
		// Increments the pos and returns the nums value at pos
        return nums[++pos];
    }

    bool hasNext() {
		// Checking for the bounding condition
        return pos+1 < nums.size();
    }
};
```
