# Approach - 1: Using vector

**Logic/Intuition:**

- This implementation uses an array to store all the elements of the BST in sorted order upfront. The iterator then simply moves through the array.


**Time Complexity:**
- The constructor (`BSTIterator`) runs in $$O(n)$$ time, where n is the number of nodes in the BST. It performs a complete in-order traversal to populate the `arr` vector.
- The `next()` and `hasNext()` functions each run in $$O(1)$$ time because retrieving an element from an array and checking if the index is within bounds are constant-time operations.

**Space Complexity:**
- The space complexity of this implementation is $$O(n)$$, where n is the number of nodes in the BST. This space is used to store all elements of the BST in the `arr` vector.

# Code
```
class BSTIterator {
public:
    vector<int> arr = {-1}; //dummy element to take care of indexing
    int idx;

    void dfs (TreeNode* root) { 
//simple inorder traversal & storing the elements in the array
        if (!root) return;
        dfs(root->left);
        arr.push_back(root->val);
        dfs(root->right);
    }

    BSTIterator(TreeNode* root) {
        dfs (root);
        idx = 0;
    }

    int next() {
        if (hasNext()) {
            idx++;
            return arr[idx];
        }
        return -1;
    }

    bool hasNext() {
        return (idx+1 < arr.size());
    }
};
```

# Approach - 2: Using stack (Optimal)
**Logic/Intuition:**
- The key idea is to use a stack to keep track of the nodes to be visited and their respective positions in the in-order traversal.

**Time Complexity:**
- The `next()` and `hasNext()` functions each run in $$O(1)$$ time on average because popping from the stack and checking if it's empty are constant-time operations. Even in the worst case, when the BST is skewed, the amortised time complexity of `next()` turns out to be $$O(1)$$.
- **This is because each element is being pushed or popped from the stack once at max in the overall run.**

**Space Complexity:**
- The space complexity of the stack used by the `BSTIterator` class is $$O(h)$$, where h is the height of the BST. In the worst case, when the BST is skewed and the height is equal to the number of nodes (n), the space complexity becomes $$O(n)$$.


# Code
```
class BSTIterator {
public:
    stack<TreeNode*> st;

    void helper (TreeNode* root) {
// helper func - push all elements to the left of the node (including the node) into the stack
        while (root) {
            st.push(root);
            root = root->left;
        }
    }

    BSTIterator(TreeNode* root) {
        helper(root); //to initialise the stack
    }

    int next() {
        if (st.empty()) return -1;
        TreeNode* node = st.top();
        st.pop();
        helper(node->right);
        return node->val;
    }

    bool hasNext() {
        return !st.empty();
    }
};
```

