To make this solution `O(h)` space, we're just keeping track of parent nodes on our stack, which will go through later (if they are eventually called by the client executing `next`).

This is how it works for `[10, 5, 15, 1, 6]`

![image](https://s3-lc-upload.s3.amazonaws.com/users/1484663199409/image_1536070104.png)

The stack will store both TreeNode and numbers. The number will be the exit point, and the TreeNode will have to be expanded. In an OO language, or if you want to make it cleaner you could actually write a class/prototype that returned you the kind of value it is storing ([just like LeetCode NestedTree in a similar problem](https://leetcode.com/problems/flatten-nested-list-iterator/)).

Initially we'll extract the root tree node, we first push the right side, then the value of the current node's and then the left side. I marked numbers as `*number*` for clarity.

`[15, *10*, 5]`

Since the popped value wasn't a number (and the stack has values left to process) we start once again.

`[15, 10, 6, *5*, 1]`

5 wasn't a number so we keep going

`[15, 10, 6, *5*, *1*]`

The TreeNode containing value 1 didn't have children. Hence the next value is going to be a number.

`[15, 10, 6, *5*]`
`this.cache = 1`

We're now done until the user requests (`next`) a new number.

```
/**
 * @constructor
 * @param {TreeNode} root - root of the binary search tree
 */
var BSTIterator = function(root) {
    this.root = root;
    this.stack = root ? [root] : [];
    this.cache;
};

BSTIterator.prototype.cacheNext = function() {
    while (this.cache === undefined && this.stack.length > 0) {
        const top = this.stack.pop();
        if (!(top instanceof TreeNode)) {
            // It's a number
            this.cache = top;
            continue;
        }

        // It's a TreeNode
        if (top.right) {
            this.stack.push(top.right);
        }
        this.stack.push(top.val);
        if (top.left) {
            this.stack.push(top.left);
        }
    }
    return this.cache;
}


/**
 * @this BSTIterator
 * @returns {boolean} - whether we have a next smallest number
 */
BSTIterator.prototype.hasNext = function() {
    return this.cacheNext() !== undefined;
};

/**
 * @this BSTIterator
 * @returns {number} - the next smallest number
 */
BSTIterator.prototype.next = function() {
    const res = this.cacheNext();
    this.cache = undefined;
    return res;
};
```

