**Idea:** The key idea here is to partition the number into 4 groups - billions, millions, thousands and the remaining digits (up to 3). All these 4 groups will have up to 3 digits and will be processed in the same way i.e. by the same function but will differ in their suffixes.
P.S.: Why is it classified as a Hard question?

```
private static final Map<Integer, String> BIG_WORD_BY_VAL = new LinkedHashMap<>();
private static final Map<Integer, String> WORD_BY_VAL = new HashMap<>();

public String numberToWords(int num) {
	if (num < 21)
		return WORD_BY_VAL.get(num);

	var ans = new StringBuilder();
	for (var entry : BIG_WORD_BY_VAL.entrySet())
		num = reduce(num, ans, entry.getKey(), entry.getValue());

	return convert(num, ans).toString()
						    .trim();
}

private int reduce(int num, StringBuilder ans, int denomination, String denominationWord) {
	if (num >= denomination) {
		convert(num / denomination, ans)).append(denominationWord);
		num %= denomination;
	}
	return num;
}

/*
There are three reductions in this method. I've explained them here sequentially:
1. Reduce by 100. This is applicable for b/millions, thousands and hundreds.
2. Reduce by 10. If quotient is 1, it means number is between [11, 19], so get name 
from map and the next block (3) will not execute, else multiply the quotient by 10 to get 
the word from map 
3. If remainder is of the form xy, where x = 2 to 9 and y != 0, e.g. 23, so "twenty three"
we don't want to do it for 20, 30 etc, because we don't say "twenty zero"
we also don't want to do it for [11, 19] because we don't say "ten one", 
they have their unique names already covered in the map
*/
private StringBuilder convert(int t, StringBuilder ans) {
	var hun = t / 100;
	if (hun != 0)
		ans.append(" ")
		   .append(WORD_BY_VAL.get(hun))
		   .append(" Hundred");
	t %= 100;

	var ten = t / 10;
	if (ten != 0) {
		ans.append(" ");
		if (ten == 1) // for 11 to 19
			ans.append(WORD_BY_VAL.get(t));
		else // for 2x to 9x
			ans.append(WORD_BY_VAL.get(ten * 10));
	}
	t %= 10;

	if (ten != 1 && t != 0)
		ans.append(" ")
		   .append(WORD_BY_VAL.get(t));

	return ans;
}

