# Intuition & Approach
Basic Intuition was that the K pairs will be generated by using at max  First K Elements  from each Arrays i.e
1. Either take all K Element from `Nums1` and one Element from `Nums2`
2. Take all K Element from `Nums2` and one Element from `Nums1`
3. Or any Combination

### Solve :-

Define a MIN Priority Queue with `Pair<int, Pair<int, int>>` to store sum, `firstArrayIndex`, `secondArrayIndex` respectively

Taking `Point 1` as Base i.e All K elements of First Array and 1 element from Second Array and storing them in MIN-HEAP

Looping K times and each time the TOP element is the Best Possible Pair

Inserting the Next Element of SecondArray to generate different Pairs


## This can also be done using by taking Point 2 as base





# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(k*log(min(n1, n2)))$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(k)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
#define pp pair<int, pair<int, int>>

class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> kSmallestPairs(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2, int k) {
        int n1 = nums1.size();
        int n2 = nums2.size();
        vector<vector<int>> ans;  

        // Create a min-heap to store pairs of indices and their sums
        priority_queue<pp, vector<pp>, greater<pp>> pq;

        // Push the initial pairs into the priority queue
        for (int i = 0; i < k && i < n1; i++)
            pq.push({nums1[i] + nums2[0], {i, 0}});

        // Process the pairs until k pairs are obtained or the priority queue is empty
        while (k > 0 && !pq.empty()) {
            // Extract the pair with the smallest sum from the priority queue
            auto curr = pq.top();
            pq.pop();

            int firstArrayIndex = curr.second.first;
            int secondArrayIndex = curr.second.second;

            // Add the pair to the answer vector
            ans.push_back({nums1[firstArrayIndex], nums2[secondArrayIndex]});

            // Push the next pair with the same first index but the next second index
            if (secondArrayIndex + 1 < n2) {
                pq.push({nums1[firstArrayIndex] + nums2[secondArrayIndex + 1], {firstArrayIndex, secondArrayIndex + 1}});
            }

            k--;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

```

