# PLEASE UPVOTE 

# Algorithm:

1. Create a priority queue `pq` to store the smallest pair sums.
2. Add pairs with the smallest sums of A[0] + B[0], A[1] + B[0], ..., A[n-1] + B[0] to the priority queue.
3. While we have not found k pairs or the priority queue is not empty, do the following:
  - Extract the pair with the smallest sum from the priority queue.
  - Add it to the output list `ans`.
  - If there are indices i and j+1 such that i < A.length and j+1 < B.length and (i, j+1) has not been visited yet, add the pair (A[i] + B[j+1], i, j+1) into the priority queue.
  - If there are indices i+1 and j such that i+1 < A.length and j < B.length and  (i+1, j) has not been visited yet, add the pair (A[i+1] + B[j], i+1, j) into the priority queue.
  - Mark (i+1, j) and (i, j+1) as visited.
4. Return `ans` as the list of k smallest pairs.



# Code
```JAVA []
record Heap(int sum,int i,int j){}  
public List<List<Integer>> kSmallestPairs(int[] A, int[] B, int k) {
    var ans = new ArrayList<List<Integer>>();
    var pq = new PriorityQueue<Heap>(Comparator.comparingInt(Heap::sum));
    int m=A.length,n=B.length;
    var set = new HashSet<String>();
    pq.add(new Heap(A[0]+B[0],0,0));
    set.add(0+","+0);
    while(k-->0 && !pq.isEmpty()){
        var pre=pq.poll();
        int i=pre.i(),j=pre.j(),p=j+1;
        ans.add(List.of(A[i],B[j]));
        if(i+1<m && !set.contains(i+1+","+j)) pq.add(new Heap(A[i+1]+B[j],i+1,j)); 
        if(j+1<n && !set.contains(i+","+p)) pq.add(new Heap(A[i]+B[j+1],i,j+1)); 
        set.add(i+1+","+j); 
        set.add(i+","+p); 
    }return ans;
}
```
```python []
import heapq
class Heap:
    def __init__(self, sum, i, j):
        self.sum, self.i, self.j = sum, i, j
    def __lt__(self, other):
        return self.sum < other.sum
def kSmallestPairs(A: List[int], B: List[int], k: int) -> List[List[int]]:
    ans, pq, m, n = [], [], len(A), len(B)
    s = set()
    heapq.heappush(pq, Heap(A[0]+B[0], 0, 0))
    s.add((0, 0))
    while k > 0 and pq:
        pre = heapq.heappop(pq)
        i, j, p = pre.i, pre.j, j+1
        ans.append([A[i], B[j]])
        if i+1 < m and (i+1, j) not in s:
            heapq.heappush(pq, Heap(A[i+1]+B[j], i+1, j))
            s.add((i+1, j))
        if j+1 < n and (i, j+1) not in s:
            heapq.heappush(pq, Heap(A[i]+B[j+1], i, j+1))
            s.add((i, j+1))
        k -= 1    
    return ans
```
```c++ []
class Heap {
public:
    int sum, i, j;
    Heap(int _sum, int _i, int _j) : sum(_sum), i(_i), j(_j) {}
    bool operator< (const Heap& other) const {
        return sum > other.sum;
    }
};
vector<vector<int>> kSmallestPairs(vector<int>& A, vector<int>& B, int k) {
    vector<vector<int>> ans;
    priority_queue<Heap> pq;
    int m = A.size(), n = B.size();
    unordered_set<string> s;
    pq.emplace(A[0] + B[0], 0, 0);
    s.insert("0,0");
    while (k-- > 0 && !pq.empty()) {
        auto pre = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        int i = pre.i, j = pre.j, p = j+1;
        ans.emplace_back(vector<int>{A[i], B[j]});
        if (i+1 < m && !s.count(to_string(i+1)+","+to_string(j))) {
            pq.emplace(A[i+1] + B[j], i+1, j);
            s.insert(to_string(i+1)+","+to_string(j));
        }
        if (j+1 < n && !s.count(to_string(i)+","+to_string(p))) {
            pq.emplace(A[i] + B[j+1], i, j+1);
            s.insert(to_string(i)+","+to_string(p));
        }
    }
    return ans;
}
```


# Time complexity:

- Adding the smallest pairs in step 2 takes O(N log N) time, where N is the length of the input arrays.
- In each iteration of the while loop in step 3, we extract a pair with the smallest sum from the priority queue, which takes O(log N) time.
- Within the while loop, we add two new pairs to the priority queue at most once, and we mark each pair as visited at most once. Therefore, we perform a constant amount of work for each iteration that doesn't extract from the priority queue, so the number of iterations of the while loop is at most k.
- Therefore, the total time complexity is O(k log N), where N is the length of the input arrays.

# Space complexity:

- We use a priority queue of size N to store the smallest pairs, so the space complexity is O(N), where N is the length of the input arrays.
- We use a set to keep track of the pairs that have already been visited, which has a maximum size of N if all pairs are unique.
- We create an output list of size k to store the k smallest pairs.
- Therefore, the total space complexity is O(N + k), where N is the length of the input arrays and k is the number of smallest pairs to be returned.

