solutions.content:
### Brute force insights
Pick K elements from nums1 and nums2 each.
Next, using K^2 pairs, pick the "K" smallest pairs using a min heap. 
However, this approach is K^2 Log(K^2) -> K^2 Log(K).
Can this be improved?

### KLog(K) Explanation using example
```text
nums1 = [1,7,11], nums2 = [2,4,6], k = 3

If you consider every (i, j) pair from nums1 and nums2, you get:-
(1, 2),  (1, 4),  (1, 6)         -  row1
(7, 2),  (7, 4),  (7, 6)         -  row2
(11, 2), (11, 4), (11, 6)        -  row3
```
Notice how the sum of pairs in each row is sorted. 
Thus, "Given k rows consisting of pairs sorted by sums, find k smallest pairs". In other words, this boils down to merge k sorted lists. 
In this problem, you can terminate early when you find "k" smallest pairs. This early termination reduces complexity to O(KLogK)

### Code
```java
    public List<List<Integer>> kSmallestPairs(int[] nums1, int[] nums2, int k) {
        // Min Heap of int array. Smallest sum pair will be at top.
        // array[0] - item in nums1, array[1] - item in nums2, array[2] - index of item in nums2 
        var pq = new PriorityQueue<int[]>(
            k, (arr1, arr2) -> (arr1[0] + arr1[1]) - (arr2[0] + arr2[1]));

        var result = new ArrayList<List<Integer>>(k);

        final int N1 = nums1.length, N2 = nums2.length;
        for (int i = 0; i < Math.min(k, N1); i++) {
            pq.add(new int[]{ nums1[i], nums2[0], 0 });
        }

        while (result.size() < k && !pq.isEmpty()) {
            var top = pq.poll();
            result.add(Arrays.asList(top[0], top[1]));

            var nextIndex = top[2] + 1;
            if (nextIndex < N2) {
                pq.add(new int[] { top[0], nums2[nextIndex], nextIndex });
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
